{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T19:51:34.235505+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 60 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 73 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":73,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":60,"completed_with_unit_data":60,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":22,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2509,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 60 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -25.1%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":452,"p25":-0.4778,"median":-0.2509,"p75":-0.0084},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.074,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 60 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +7.4%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":60,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":60,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.0927,"mean":0.1287,"median":0.074,"p25":-0.1001,"p50":0.074,"p75":0.277,"p10":-0.2003,"p90":0.495},"median_actual_dollars":252098.75},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~120 hours per plumbing unit","value":120.1568,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 120.2 hrs/unit (P25 102, P75 143). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 102 and 143 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":60,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":163.0536,"median":120.1568,"p25":101.6543,"p50":120.1568,"p75":142.9956,"p10":75.3739,"p90":165.6673,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 38.1%","value":0.3815,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 38.1%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":60,"p25":0.311,"median":0.3815,"p75":0.4524},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$42.08/hr (1.42\u00d7 blended)","value":42.078,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $42.08/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.42\u00d7 means OWP carries ~42% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":29.3157,"loaded_wage_median":42.078,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4209},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.7% median)","value":-0.1565,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.7%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":572,"min":-0.9914,"max":3.4135,"mean":-0.0973,"median":-0.1565,"p25":-0.4025,"p50":-0.1565,"p75":0.093,"p10":-0.5976,"p90":0.4313},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":60,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":163.0536,"median":120.1568,"p25":101.6543,"p50":120.1568,"p75":142.9956,"p10":75.3739,"p90":165.6673,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":60,"min":1419.3979,"max":90082.0,"mean":5134.174,"median":3626.2917,"p25":2864.5844,"p50":3626.2917,"p75":4248.1057,"p10":1987.834,"p90":5227.9451,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":60,"min":1219.6971,"max":58415.81,"mean":4644.4327,"median":3618.507,"p25":2897.154,"p50":3618.507,"p75":4426.166,"p10":2089.458,"p90":5138.0097,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":60,"min":7181.5,"max":350295.0,"mean":21265.565,"median":16063.299,"p25":12588.624,"p50":16063.299,"p75":18265.9407,"p10":10142.2403,"p90":21011.8191,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":60,"min":0.1089,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2355,"median":0.2312,"p25":0.2105,"p50":0.2312,"p75":0.2698,"p10":0.1851,"p90":0.289,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":60,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3135,"mean":0.2363,"median":0.2354,"p25":0.2177,"p50":0.2354,"p75":0.2653,"p10"